[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1064},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F16\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F16\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F16\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F16\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read\u002F":1039,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F16\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read\u002F":1048},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20220216\u002F326471867\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1021,"date":1022,"description":1023,"extension":1024,"lang":1025,"meta":1026,"navigation":689,"path":1027,"readingMinutes":1028,"seo":1029,"standalone":1030,"stem":1031,"tags":1032,"tldr":1036,"updated":1022,"url":1037,"__hash__":1038},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-frontend-04-mongodb-crud-read.md","(4) The Frontend Dev Forced to Eat Mango - MongoDB CRUD: Read","1003310145",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1008},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,32,37,44,51,61,67,73,76,81,88,128,134,144,148,151,615,618,624,627,633,636,641,652,657,660,710,716,721,725,730,749,755,759,765,782,788,800,818,823,827,833,836,854,860,864,872,890,896,899,903,909,932,938,962,967,971,976,999,1004],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"By now we've inserted a bunch of data into MongoDB. But here's the thing — how do we actually know it made it in there? So next up, let's learn the query syntax.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"read","Read",[17,25,26,27,31],{},"It says Read, but honestly the concept is closer to searching (Query). In MongoDB land, the most basic search syntax is ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"db.collection.find()",".",[17,33,34,36],{},[28,35,30],{}," decides what to return based on what you pass in. If you pass nothing at all, it just lists everything.",[17,38,39],{},[40,41],"img",{"alt":42,"src":43},"find","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-23%2000.05.46.png",[17,45,46,47,50],{},"Fun fact: if you type ",[28,48,49],{},"db.users.find({})",", it also returns all the data.",[17,52,53,54,57,58,31],{},"Mapped to SQL, ",[28,55,56],{},"db.users.find()"," is basically the same as ",[28,59,60],{},"SELECT * FROM users",[17,62,63,64,31],{},"If you want to search by a specific property, you pass in a property and a value. Say I want to find users who are 28 years old — you'd write ",[28,65,66],{},"db.users.find({ age: 28 })",[17,68,69],{},[40,70],{"alt":71,"src":72},"specific search","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-23%2000.50.13.png",[17,74,75],{},"One thing to watch out for with this kind of search: if there are multiple matching results, it returns all of them. For example, searching for age 25 brings back everyone who's 25.",[17,77,78],{},[40,79],{"alt":71,"src":80},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-23%2000.51.55.png",[17,82,83,84,87],{},"This is the same as using ",[28,85,86],{},"WHERE",":",[89,90,95],"pre",{"className":91,"code":92,"language":93,"meta":94,"style":94},"language-sql shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","SELECT * FROM users WHERE age = \"28\"\n","sql","",[28,96,97],{"__ignoreMap":94},[98,99,102,106,109,112,116,118,121,124],"span",{"class":100,"line":101},"line",1,[98,103,105],{"class":104},"sWyjQ","SELECT",[98,107,108],{"class":104}," *",[98,110,111],{"class":104}," FROM",[98,113,115],{"class":114},"sMAXC"," users ",[98,117,86],{"class":104},[98,119,120],{"class":114}," age ",[98,122,123],{"class":104},"=",[98,125,127],{"class":126},"sTRMh"," \"28\"\n",[17,129,130,131,31],{},"You can also pass in multiple field conditions: ",[28,132,133],{},"db.users.find({ age: 25, name: 'Roy' })",[17,135,136,137,140,141,31],{},"And if you only want the first matching document, use ",[28,138,139],{},"findOne",", like this: ",[28,142,143],{},"db.users.findOne({ age: 25, name: 'Roy' })",[12,145,147],{"id":146},"conditional-queries","Conditional queries",[17,149,150],{},"So in real-world database usage, do we really only ever query by a single field? Of course not. To make the practice later easier, I'd suggest pasting in the following code to seed some data:",[89,152,156],{"className":153,"code":154,"language":155,"meta":94,"style":94},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","db.users.insertMany([\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Clayton Jimenez\",\n    \"age\": 15,\n    \"status\": false\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Annie Barrett\",\n    \"age\": 38,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Monica Hale\",\n    \"age\": 56,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Monica Curtis\",\n    \"age\": 35,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Sarah Rodriquez\",\n    \"age\": 22,\n    \"status\": false\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Michael Austin\",\n    \"age\": 29,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Josephine Roberts\",\n    \"age\": 25,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Reginald Hall\",\n    \"age\": 29,\n    \"status\": false\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Letitia Fields\",\n    \"age\": 14,\n    \"status\": false\n  },\n  {\n    \"name\": \"Judith Ramirez\",\n    \"age\": 48,\n    \"status\": true\n  },\n])\n","js",[28,157,158,170,176,191,205,216,222,227,239,251,261,266,271,283,295,304,309,314,326,338,347,352,357,369,381,390,395,400,412,424,433,438,443,455,467,476,481,486,498,509,518,523,528,540,552,561,566,571,583,595,604,609],{"__ignoreMap":94},[98,159,160,163,167],{"class":100,"line":101},[98,161,162],{"class":114},"db.users.",[98,164,166],{"class":165},"sj_SG","insertMany",[98,168,169],{"class":114},"([\n",[98,171,173],{"class":100,"line":172},2,[98,174,175],{"c